What Would Chief Justice Roberts Do?
¶

*An Analysis and Prediction of Conservative/Liberal Votes.*
¶

An Hoang

Introduction
¶

The Supreme Court is an important institution in the United States as its decisions on the cases it reviews (or even cases it chooses not to review) can have a sweeping impact on individuals and organization not just in America, but around the world. In recent times, the Court has ruled on cases involving hot-button topics such as abortion, religion, criminal law, immigration, constitutional powers of government, and voting rights. There are 9 sitting Supreme Court justices - 8 associate Justices and 1 Chief Justice, CJ Roberts. Two of the associate Justices (Gorsuch and Kavanaugh) are recent additions, replacing the late Justice Scalia and retired Justice Kennedy. Appointed by President Trump, Justice Gorsuch and Justice Kavanaugh are viewed as conservative Justices that have swung the Supreme Court's ideological tendencies to the right. In effect, Chief Justice Roberts, also viewed as a relatively conservative judge in the past, is now considered by some to be the Court's ideological center (i.e., the swing vote). See here.

Given the importance of the issues considered by the Supreme Court, there are a number of observers that track and analyze the Court's decisions. There are even publications regarding the voting tendencies of each individual Justice and academic articles that seek to quantify those tendencies. For example, see here and here. The idea is that if we can accurately predict each Justice's particular inclinations and understand their judicial philosophy, we can predict the outcome of each case argued before the Court.

In this tutorial, the goal is to explore and analyze past Supreme Court cases and gain insight into which variables might be successful in predicting how a Supreme Court Justice might vote on any specific case. Specifically, this tutorial seeks to provide an accurate model for predicting how Chief Justice Roberts may vote on a case, based on specific case attributes. Models for other Justices may be explored using similar means described in the tutorial below. Inspiration was taken from the paper by Lee Epstein & Andrew D. Martin published in 2011 analyzing "The Voting Behavior of Clarence Thomas." This tutorial seeks to expand on that paper using updated data through 2018 and introduce a model for predicting the vote of a Supreme Court Justice.

Getting Started / Getting Data
¶

We use python3 along with various imported libraries (pandas, numpy, scipy, matplotlib, scikit-learn, and seaborn) for data analyis, visualization, and prediction.

Supreme Court case data is from the Supreme Court Database managed by Washington University School of Law

Martin-Quinn Scores are from Professors Martin and Quinn at University of Michigan.

Supreme Court Case data¶

The Supreme Court Case data comes in a variety of formats. One choice to make is to either get Case centered data or Justice centered data. Case centered data provide case-level information in each row, but does not provide granular information regarding how each Justice voted on each case. Therefore, we use the Justice centered data which includes a set of justice votes for each dispute. The data comes different file formats as well, such as .csv, Rdata, and .xlsx. We use the .xlsx format to import into a pandas dataframe as it's the most straightforward method.

In the Supreme Court Case dataset, there are quite a lot of columns - many of which we do not need for the purposes of this analysis. For example, the dataset includes bibliographic information about each case, such as the id, docket, decision date, citations, etc. We drop many of these columns in the next section to make the dataset size more manageable. However, some of these columns may provide fertile ground for further exploration and analysis for predictive value. Among the columns that we do keep in this tutorial, we include:

  • adminAction (whether the case arose from an administrative case)
  • lcDipositionDirection (whether the lower court ruled conservatively or liberally)
  • issueArea (the nature of key legal issue in the case)
  • direction (whether the Justice voted conservatively or liberally)

The column names are generally self-explanatory but some columns are encoded with values, such as justice, vote, opinion, direction, lawType, etc. To learn more about these encoded values, see the Supreme Court Database website for documentation on each column.

Martin-Quinn Scores¶

Martin-Quinn Scores is a calculated statistic devised by Andrew D. Martin and Kevin M. Quinn. The MQ Scores employ Markov chain Monte Carlo methods to fit a Bayesian measurement model of ideal points (policy preferences on a one-dimensional scale) for all the Justices based on the votes in every contested Supreme Court case since 1937. See here.

In a nutshell, MS Scores measure the relative location of U.S. Supreme Court justices on an ideological continuum. We introduce these scores as another potential predictor of how likely a justice may vote conservatively vs. liberally.

The MS Scores are based on the Supreme Court Case dataset above, and therefore align quite nicely with that dataset.

Exploratory Data Analysis
¶

For this section, we perform some calculations in order to get a high-level view of Justice voting patterns. We use seaborn to create some nice looking graphs to more easily visualize the information.

Calculating the Voting Record of Each Justice¶

First, we calculate the frequency each Justice voted conservatively for the cases they participated in. This is easily done by summing the occasions where the Justice voted conservatively and liberally and doing some basic division.

% of conservative votes $ = \frac{\sum(Conservative Votes)}{\sum(Conservative Votes) + \sum(Liberal Votes)}$

In addition, the calculating this percentage for all cases the Justice participated in, we can also calculate this percentage of conservative votes for a specific subset of cases based on the main legal issue. Below, we calculate the percentage of conservative votes for Civil Rights Cases and Federalism Cases. For this tutorial, we choose Civil Rights and Federalism as important areas of law that assumably presents a clear divide for liberal/conservative ideologies, but we can also choose other types of cases like criminal procedure or privacy. See here.

In [39]:
#get a list of all the Justices and initialize some empty arrays to store calculations
justiceList = df.justiceName.unique()
votingRecord = []
votingRecordCL = []
votingRecordFed = []

#iterate through the list of justices
for i in justiceList:
    
    #Sum the number of times each individual justice voted conservatively/liberally
    cons = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 1)])
    lib = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 2)])
    #calculate the % of conservative votes
    perc = cons/(cons+lib)
    #append calculation to the list
    votingRecord.append(perc)
    
    #Same as above, but targeting only Civil Rights cases (where issueArea coded as the number 2)
    cons = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 1) & (df.issueArea == 2)])
    lib = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 2) & (df.issueArea == 2)])
    perc = cons/(cons+lib)
    votingRecordCL.append(perc)
    
    #Same as above, but targeting only Federalism cases (where issueArea coded as the number 10)
    cons = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 1) & (df.issueArea == 10)])
    lib = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 2) & (df.issueArea == 10)])
    perc = cons/(cons+lib)
    votingRecordFed.append(perc)

#setting up data to create a new DataFrame
votingPercData = {'justiceName': justiceList,
                  'percAllCases': votingRecord,
                  'percCivilRights': votingRecordCL,
                  'percFederalism': votingRecordFed}
    
votingPerc = pd.DataFrame(votingPercData)

#sorting justices by their proportion of conservative votes
votingPerc.sort_values(by=['percAllCases'], ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

We can see from the table output above that some of our more recent justices top the charts in terms of their proportion of conservative votes. Justices Thomas, Scalia, Gorsuch, Kavanaugh, Kennedy, and Roberts are in the top 15 of justices since 1946. Justices Kagan, Ginsburg, and Sotomayor are in the bottom 15 of justices in terms of their proportion of conservative votes.

Breaking the results down into different types of cases, we can also see that the Justices are generally consistent in their proportion of conservative votes for Civil Rights cases and Federalism cases. Note that Justices Gorsuch and Kavanaugh have a 100% conservative voting record for Federalism cases partially because of a small sample size (they are our two newest associate Justices).

Calculating the MQ Score for Each Justice¶

Next, we calculate the average Martin-Quinn Scores for each Justice so that we may see if these scores generally align with the proportion of conservative votes. This is easily done with DataFrames.

In [38]:
#Grouping the data by Justice and averaging each Justice's MQ Score across the terms they were active
avgMQ = MQScores.groupby('justiceName')['post_mn'].mean()

#merging the MS Scores with the previous dataset
comb = votingPerc.merge(avgMQ, left_on='justiceName', right_on='justiceName')

#sorting the table by the MQ Score
comb.sort_values(by=['post_mn'], ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

Graphing the Data for Visualization¶

Perhaps there's an easier way to digest this information? We can chart the data above into bar charts using seaborn.

Graphing Data Over Time¶

What about changes over time? Do Justices generally stay consistent in their judicial philosophies and maintain the same proportion of conservative votes? We can plot the data over time, again with seaborn.

First, we re-calculate the proportion of conservative votes for each Justice, but this time also by year.

In [11]:
#df.groupby(['term', 'justiceName'])

#Get the list of years and justice names
justiceList = df.justiceName.unique()
yearList = df.term.unique()

#initialize some arrays to store calculations
votingRecord = []
votingRecordCL = []
votingRecordFed = []
justiceRecord = []
yearRecord = []

#iterate through the years and justices to calculate the proportion of conservative votes for each justice for each year
for j in yearList:
    for i in justiceList:
        
        #get the number of conservative votes and liberal votes for each justice in each year
        cons = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 1) & (df.term == j)])
        lib = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 2) & (df.term == j)])
        
        #if the justice was not active that year, then default to 0; else calculate the value
        if (cons+lib) == 0:
            perc = 0
        else:
            perc = cons/(cons+lib)
        votingRecord.append(perc)
        
        #same as above,  but only calcualte for Civil Rights cases (where issueArea is coded as the number 2)
        cons = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 1) & (df.issueArea == 2) & (df.term == j)])
        lib = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 2) & (df.issueArea == 2) & (df.term == j)])
        if (cons+lib) == 0:
            perc = 0
        else:
            perc = cons/(cons+lib)
        votingRecordCL.append(perc)
    
        #same as above,  but only calcualte for Federalism cases (where issueArea is coded as the number 10)
        cons = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 1) & (df.issueArea == 10) & (df.term == j)])
        lib = len(df[(df.justiceName == i) & (df.direction == 2) & (df.issueArea == 10) & (df.term == j)])
        if (cons+lib) == 0:
            perc = 0
        else:
            perc = cons/(cons+lib)
        votingRecordFed.append(perc)
        
        yearRecord.append(j)
        justiceRecord.append(i)

#setup the data to create a new DataFrame
votingByYearData = {'term': yearRecord,
                  'justiceName': justiceRecord,
                  'percAllCases': votingRecord,
                  'percCivilRights': votingRecordCL,
                  'percFederalism': votingRecordFed}

Predicting Chief Justice Roberts' Vote
¶

At this point, we can try to develop a model that accurately predicts Roberts' vote (conservative or liberal) based various characteristics. Since our dependent variable is binary, we use a logistic regression model.

In [43]:
#Get data for CJ Roberts
roberts = df[df.justiceName == 'JGRoberts']
roberts = roberts[roberts.term != 2005]

#shift MQ Score to use as a predictor for the next term (e.g., 2005 MQ Score is used to predict 2006 outcome)
new = combYear[['term', 'justiceName', 'post_mn']].copy()
new = new[new.justiceName == 'JGRoberts']
new['term'] = new['term']+1
new.drop(new.tail(1).index,inplace=True)
#display(new)

#merge the year-adjusted MQ scores with the Supreme Court case dataset
totalcomb = roberts.merge(new, on=['term', 'justiceName'])

#drop some more extraneous columns
toDrop = ['petitioner','respondent','decisionDirection', 'decisionDirectionDissent', 'majVotes', 'minVotes', 'justiceName', 'majority']
totalcomb.drop(toDrop, axis=1, inplace=True)

#create some dummy variables for the model
totalcomb['lc_cons'] = totalcomb['lcDispositionDirection'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 2.0 else 0)
totalcomb['lc_lib'] = totalcomb['lcDispositionDirection'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 1.0 else 0)

totalcomb['isCivilRights'] = totalcomb['issueArea'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 2.0 else 0)
totalcomb['isFederalism'] = totalcomb['issueArea'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 10.0 else 0)
totalcomb['isCrimPro'] = totalcomb['issueArea'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 1.0 else 0)
totalcomb['isDueProcess'] = totalcomb['issueArea'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 4.0 else 0)
totalcomb['isPrivacy'] = totalcomb['issueArea'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 5.0 else 0)

totalcomb['isAdminAction'] = totalcomb['adminAction'].apply(lambda x: 0 if pd.isnull(x) else 1)

import statsmodels.api as sm

#drop the rows where the vote direction (conservative or liberal) is not measured

#set up the variables for the logistic regression

#we subtract 1 here because the original data codes 1 as "liberal" and 2 as "conservative"
y = totalcomb['direction']-1

#create the model and print the model summary
logit_model=sm.Logit(y,X)
result=logit_model.fit()
print(result.summary2())

We see our model summary has evaluated the statistical significance of each coefficient for the variables included in the logistic model. Based on the p-values, the lower court decision (lc_cons/lc_lib), whether the legal was federalism, criminal procedure, and privacy, and whether the case arose from an administrative action were all significant. However, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the coefficients for civil rights, Due Process, and MQ Score are 0 (i.e., not statistically significant). This is a little surprising, given that MQ Score is supposed to be a measure of a Justice's ideological leaning. It may be due to the face that the MQ Score is calculated off of the same dataset so its predictive power is weakened.

Upon reviewing these results, we can trim out model down to the signififant coefficients.

Accuracy of logistic regression classifier on test set: 0.67

Based on our testing, the accuracy of our logistic model is about 67%. A little disappointing that it's not higher but our odds of correctly predicting Chief Justice Robert's vote based on the lower court's decision and a few case classifications is 2:1. All in all, given the difficulty in capturing the nuance of legal jurisprudence and the nature of legal cases, our model's accuracy is not terrible.

Conclusions¶

After reviewing the data and the logistic model, it appears that we can predict to some degrees of certainty whether Chief Justice Roberts will vote conservatively or liberally on any given case. Our current model is not quite reliable, being only 67% accurate on the testing data but there are other variables that could be introduced to increase the model's robustness. For example, there are other legal issues categories that could be examined (Judicial Power, First Amendment, Interstate Relations), we could see whether specific Parties to the case (e.g. the U.S. government) have any predictive power, or introduce variables capturing other case aspects like jurisdiction and origin. We could also add other non-case data aside from MQ Score, such as the party of the President who appointed the Justice.

In any case, this tutorial can also be applied to other justices, both past and present, and potentially to the Court as a whole. Being able to predict even just one Justice's inclination to vote conservatively or liberally for a yet-undecided case would be an immensely powerful tool for a wide audience of interested observers.
